<bdy>

<indent level="1">

<it>The </it>'logit<b> function is an important part of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../631/226631.xml">
logistic regression</link>: for more information, please see that article.</b></indent>

The <b>logit</b> function is the inverse of the "sigmoid", or <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../563/84563.xml">
"logistic" function</link> used in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../831/18831.xml">
mathematics</link>, especially in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../685/26685.xml">
statistics</link>. The <b>logit</b> of a number <it>p</it> between 0 and 1 is given by the formula:<p>

<indent level="1">

<math>\operatorname{logit}(p)=\log\left( \frac{p}{1-p} \right) =\log(p)-\log(1-p). \!\,</math>
</indent>

<b>Logit</b> is pronounced  with a long "o" and a soft "g".</p>
<p>

The base of the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../860/17860.xml">
logarithm</link> function used is of little importance in the present article, as long as it is greater than 1, but the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../476/21476.xml">
natural logarithm</link> with base <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../633/9633.xml">
e</link> is the one most often used.</p>
<p>

If <it>p</it> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../934/22934.xml">
probability</link> then <it>p</it>/(1 &amp;minus; <it>p</it>) is the corresponding <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../069/172069.xml">
odds</link>, and the logit of the probability is the logarithm of the odds; similarly the difference between the logits of two probabilities is the logarithm of the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../880/406880.xml">
odds ratio</link> (<it>R</it>), thus providing a shorthand for writing the correct combination of odds-ratios <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../372/87372.xml">
only by adding and subtracting</link>:</p>
<p>

<indent level="1">

<math>\operatorname{log}(R)=\log\left( \frac{{p_1}/(1-p_1)}{{p_2}/(1-p_2)} \right) =\log\left( \frac{p_1}{1-p_1} \right) - \log\left(\frac{p_2}{1-p_2}\right)=\operatorname{logit}(p_1)-\operatorname{logit}(p_2). \!\,</math>
</indent>

