Plot of <it>logit(p)</it> in the domain of 0 to 1, where the base of logarithm is <it>e''</it>
</caption>
</image>
</p>

<sec>
<st>
History</st>
<p>

The logit model was introduced by <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<peer wordnetid="109626238" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<statistician wordnetid="110653238" confidence="0.8">
<colleague wordnetid="109935990" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.8">
<mathematician wordnetid="110301261" confidence="0.8">
<associate wordnetid="109816771" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../090/9875090.xml">
Joseph Berkson</link></associate>
</mathematician>
</scientist>
</causal_agent>
</colleague>
</statistician>
</person>
</peer>
</physical_entity>
 in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../622/34622.xml">
1944</link>, who coined the term. The term was borrowed by analogy from the very similar <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../101/1689101.xml">
probit</link> model developed by <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<statistician wordnetid="110653238" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.8">
<mathematician wordnetid="110301261" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../865/14264865.xml">
Chester Ittner Bliss</link></mathematician>
</scientist>
</causal_agent>
</statistician>
</person>
</physical_entity>
 in 1934. <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../579/2792579.xml">
G. A. Barnard</link> in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../604/34604.xml">
1949</link> coined the commonly used term <it>log-odds</it>; the log-odds of an event is the logit of the probability of the event.</p>

</sec>
<sec>
<st>
Uses and properties</st>

<p>

<list>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 The <b>logit</b> in logistic regression is a special case of a link function in a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../122/747122.xml">
generalized linear model</link>: it is the canonical <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../122/747122.xml">
link function</link> for the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../876/3876.xml">
binomial distribution</link>.</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 The <b>logit</b> function is the negative of the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../921/7921.xml">
derivative</link> of the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../277/5275277.xml">
binary entropy function</link>.</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 The <b>logit</b> is also central to the probabilistic <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<model wordnetid="110324560" confidence="0.8">
<assistant wordnetid="109815790" confidence="0.8">
<worker wordnetid="109632518" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../615/2161615.xml">
Rasch model</link></causal_agent>
</worker>
</assistant>
</model>
</person>
</physical_entity>
 for <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../022/19022.xml">
measurement</link>, which has applications in psychological and educational assessment, among other areas.</entry>
</list>
</p>

